Women wait to receive mine waste material to separete cobalt from mud and rocks in a mine between Lubumbashi and Kolwezi on May 31, 2015. Photo: VCGTwo Chinese were killed in a mine in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) on Sunday local time when armed militants raided the mine.More than 10 armed militants attacked a mine in the Manbasa area of Ituri province Sunday morning local time. They burned vehicles, stole valuables and killed three mine employees, including the two Chinese.The remaining Chinese employees were evacuated from the area, the Xinhua News Agency reported on Tuesday.The Chinese Embassy in DRC urged local authorities to conduct an in-depth investigation into the incident and to take effective measures to protect the lives and property of Chinese people who live there."It is not a terrorist attack. The area is often attacked by armed militants," an employee at the embassy told the Global Times on Tuesday, noting that it will release an announcement on further details soon after the investigation of the local police.Congo is Africa's leading copper producer, having mined 1.03 million tons of the metal in 2014. China will not pick sides in India-Pakistan disputesF-35 fighter jet plan 'not aimed at China'China-US trade deal must be fair, equal Surprising discovery'Super' bloom